🧱 1. Basic Structure (single variable)
docker run -e KEY=VALUE IMAGE

👉 Example:

docker run -e MY_NAME=Harpreet ubuntu
🧱 2. Multiple Variables Structure
docker run -e KEY1=VALUE1 -e KEY2=VALUE2 -e KEY3=VALUE3 IMAGE

👉 Example:

docker run -it \
  -e MY_NAME=Harpreet \
  -e APP_ENV=dev \
  -e PORT=5000 \
  ubuntu bash
🧱 3. Using --env-file
docker run --env-file filename IMAGE

👉 Example:

docker run -it --env-file .env ubuntu bash
🧱 4. Full Combined Structure
docker run [OPTIONS] \
  -e KEY=VALUE \
  --env-file file.env \
  IMAGE \
  COMMAND

👉 Example:

docker run -it \
  -e DEBUG=true \
  --env-file .env \
  ubuntu bash
🧠 General Formula
docker run + options + environment variables + image + command
🔍 Breakdown
docker run → container start
-e KEY=VALUE → ek variable set
--env-file → multiple variables file se
IMAGE → jaise Ubuntu
COMMAND → jaise bash
🎯 Pro Tip
Few variables → use -e
Many variables → use --env-file
Permanent → use Dockerfile (ENV)


-d ka matlab hota hai detached mode 👇

🔍 Command
docker run -d IMAGE

Using Docker, this means:

👉 Container background me run karega, terminal ko block nahi karega

🧠 Simple samajh
Without -d → container foreground me chalta hai (terminal busy)
With -d → container background me chalta hai (terminal free)
📦 Example
docker run -d nginx

👉 Yeh:

Nginx container start karega
Background me run karega
Tumhara terminal free rahega
📤 Output kya aata hai?
a1b2c3d4e5f6...

👉 Yeh container ID hota hai

🔎 Check running containers
docker ps
📜 Logs dekhne ke liye
docker logs <container_id>
🛑 Stop karne ke liye
docker stop <container_id>
🎯 Real Use

-d use hota hai jab:

Web server run karna ho
Database run karna ho
Long-running service chalani ho
🆚 Quick Comparison
Mode	Behavior
-it	interactive (andar jaake kaam karo)
-d	background (service chalti rahe)
🧠 Easy line yaad rakhne ke liye

-d = “run and disappear (background me chala ja)”
